Along with the doping, the role of surface functionalization on QDs is studied with the chemical treatment of DA and their alteration to the optical properties of these QDs is also investigated with pH (Figs. 2 and 3

                     ). The upper panel of Fig. 2 represents the spectroscopic characterizations of CDs in three different pH's (acidic pH 3, neutral pH 7, and alkaline pH 10). The pristine as-synthesized CDs at different pH do not show any appreciable change in steady-state (Fig. 2a and b) and time-resolved spectral measurements (Fig. 2c, Table 1
                     ), however, DA surface attachment to CDs is observed to be significantly perturbing their spectral features (lower panel of Fig. 2). The absorption spectra of DCDs (Fig. 2d, dashed line) give the characteristics of both DA and CDs with a red shift in the excitonic peak for CDs from ∼340 nm to ∼355 nm (Fig. S2a), indicating the formation of an amide bond in the complex system [43]. The appearance of both the peaks in the single spectra and the emergence of an amide bond can be accredited to the successful attachment of DA on CDs surfaces.

The PL intensity of DCDs decreases with neutral and alkaline pH with emission maxima at 460 nm (Fig. 2d, solid line), with a similar trend for excitation maxima at ∼370 nm (Fig. 2d, dotted line). The control measurement of the absorption and PL spectra of only DA samples in different pH is also carried out for checking any direct contribution to CDs. The pH variation from neutral to alkaline increases the optical density along with shifting the absorption peak ∼16 nm towards the red end (Fig. S3a). This is ascribed to the increase in the conjugation of the oxidation product in accordance with the molecular structure of DA-QN in an alkaline medium (Scheme S1) [44]. With an excitation of 280 nm, the emission peak of DA is observed to be at 320 nm for different pH (Fig. S3b), indicating no features or interference in the emissive range of CDs around 460 nm. Similarly, in another control experiment, with excitation at 370 nm, (far away from the absorption maxima of DA), we observe there is no emission of DA, indicating that the DA emission does not interfere, while we excite the CDs (Fig. S4). As reported in previous literature, DA in acidic pH remains in the HQN form, acting as an electron donor, and at an elevated pH, DA undergoes oxidation to form DA-QN which acts as an electron acceptor [45,46]. For instance, the charge transfer interaction in covalently assembled QD-DA conjugates has been explored by Ji et al. showing the effect of medium pH on PL quenching [47]. They have recorded higher PL quenching efficiencies and prominent shortening in PL lifetime for alkaline medium compared to the acidic medium. These results are ascribed to the charge transfer interactions between QDs and two forms of DA, first is the ET from reduced DA (catechol) to the valence band of QDs, and second is ET interactions between QDs and the oxidized form of DA (quinone). Similar studies on ET between other nanostructures and DA are also reported and are in line with our measurements [20,48]. Hence, the PL quenching of CDs with DA is plausible as CDs have both electron-donating and accepting capabilities [19,49]. Another interesting observation for the DA-attached CDs is that the excitation-dependent PL (EDPL) behavior of CDs has changed to excitation-independent PL (EIDPL), irrespective of the nature of pH (Fig. S5). As the excitation wavelength is increased from 280 to 450 nm, the emission peak of CDs is red-shifted from 285 nm to 515 nm (Fig. 2b), however, DCDs display an EIDPL behavior with a fixed emission maximum at 461 nm when excited at varying wavelengths (Fig. 2e). For a particular λex = 370 nm, DA attachment shifts the CDs emission peak from 445 nm to 461 nm (Inset of Fig. 2e, Fig. S6a), indicating the successful DA attachment. It is reported that CDs have many surface-emissive states corresponding to different energy levels, which are localized to a single energy level after the surface states are passivated with amino groups. So, after attachment or doping, the emission comes from a single state resulting in EIDPL behavior in DCDs [50]. Furthermore, the DA attachment in CDs brings interesting alteration in the excited state photo-dynamics with a decrement in the average decay lifetime from ∼4 ns in the case of CDs (Fig. 2c) to ∼2 ns after attachment (Fig. 2f). This is assigned to the ET in the conjugated systems [49]. In basic pH, the reduced lifetime in DCDs (from 2.14 ns to 1.57 ns for pH-3 to 10) is attributed to the ET between DA and CDs (Fig. 2f, Table S4). Thus, to quantify the ET process between DA and CDs, we have determined the ET efficiency (η

                        ET
                     ) as 58.7% in neutral pH, 50.5% in acidic pH, and 64.0% in basic pH (
                        Equation-5
                     ). This indicates a higher ET is plausible in basic pH, which is in congruence with the literature reported by Medintz et al. for DA functionalized CdSe/ZnS core/shell QDs [15]. An increase in pH induces oxidation to quinone form facilitating the ET process from CDs to DA, hence resulting in shortening the PL lifetime of CDs. Furthermore, to corroborate the DA attachment in CDs, we have performed FTIR spectroscopic measurements of DCDs, as shown in Fig. S7. After functionalization with DA in CDs (Fig. S7, blue), two strong peaks at 1577 cm−1 (N–H bending), 1650 cm−1 (CO stretching), a small peak at 3232 cm−1 (N–H stretching in primary amides, –NH2) with a peak at 3315 cm−1 (N–H stretching in secondary amides, –NH), indicate the presence of amide group [51]. This proves the successful attachment of DA on the surface of CDs. The additional peaks at 1340 cm−1 and 1157 cm−1 are due to the C–N stretching of DA [52].

To identify the nature and mode of CTp, we have tried to fit the I–V curves with several electrode-limited conduction mechanisms like Schottky emission ( Equation (6) , Fig. S15) and thermionic field emission ( Equation (7) , Fig. S16). However, we have achieved the best fit for the quantum tunneling model with direct and FN tunneling ( Equation (8) ) for the lower and higher bias region, respectively [61,67]. According to Simmon's model, electrons can tunnel through a trapezoidal barrier showing direct (non-resonant) tunneling, when the applied voltage is less than the barrier height (
φ
), and when the bias voltage surpasses φ, the electrons tunnel through a triangular barrier, exhibiting field emission (FN tunneling) [68]. In the lower bias region, the I–V curves are linear which changes to nonlinear at a higher bias regime (FN tunneling). A schematic showing the mechanism of direct and FN tunneling is given in Scheme 2b.
